We visualize this proposition in Figure 1 and defer its proof to the appendix. In this proposition, "a set s is a  cover of a set s " means a set of balls with radius  centered at each member of s can cover the entire s . Informally, this proposition suggests that we can bound the core-set loss with covering radius and a term which goes to zero with rate depends solely on n. This is an interesting result since this bound does not depend on the number of labelled points. In other words, a provided label does not help the core-set loss unless it decreases the covering radius.

In order to show that this bound applies to CNNs, we prove the Lipschitz-continuity of the loss function of a CNN with the following lemma where max-pool and restricted linear units are the non-linearities and the loss is defined as the l2 distance between the desired probabilities and the soft-max outputs.

