Unfortunately this problem is NP-Hard (Cook et al., 1998). However, it is possible to obtain a 2 - OP T solution efficiently using a greedy approach shown in Algorithm 1. If OP T = mins1 maxi minjs1s0 (xi, xj), the greedy algorithm shown in Algorithm 1 is proven to have a solution (s1) such that; maxi minjs1s0 (xi, xj)  2 × OP T .
Although the greedy algorithm gives a good initialization, in practice we can improve the 2 - OP T solution by iteratively querying upper bounds on the optimal value. In other words, we can design an algorithm which decides if OP T  . In order to do so, we define a mixed integer program (MIP) parametrized by  such that its feasibility indicates mins1 maxi minjs1s0 (xi, xj)  . A straight-forward algorithm would be to use this MIP as a sub-routine and performing a binary search between the result of the greedy algorithm and its half since the optimal solution is guaranteed to be included in that range. While constructing this MIP, we also try to handle one of the weaknesses of k-Center algorithm, namely robustness. To make the k-Center problem robust, we assume an upper limit on the number of outliers  such that our algorithm can choose not to cover at most  unsupervised data points. This mixed integer program can be written as:

